Welcome to Our Anomaly Detection Project

Implemented By - Pankaj Solanki

Group - Data Analytics

Algorithms Implemented are Isolation Forest , One-Class SVM, Microsoft Anomaly Detector and LOF

1.Overview¶

Project Details¶

 In this project, we use NAB-dataset, which is a novel benchmark for evaluating algorithms for anomaly detection in several fields.There are 58 timeseries data from various kind of sources.
  1. Real data
    • realAWSCloudwatch
    • realAdExchange
    • realKnownCause
    • realTraffic
    • realTweets
  2. Artificial data
    • artificialNoAnomaly
    • artificialWithAnomaly
    In these dataset above, I picked up and analyzed 'machine_temperature_system_failure' from realKnownCause dataset based on my buissiness interests.

Goal of this project¶

  • Practice data pre-processing technique
  • Practice EDA technique to deal with time-series data
  • Practice visualising technique
  • Practice anomaly detection modeling technique(Isolation Forest)
  • Practice improving model interpretability technique(SHAP)

3. Load the dataset¶

As above, we use 'machine_temperature_system_failure.csv' for our analysis.
According to dataset information, it has the following features :
  • Temperature sensor data of an internal component of a large, industrial mahcine.
  • The first anomaly is a planned shutdown of the machine.
  • The second anomaly is difficult to detect and directly led to the third anomaly, a catastrophic failure of the machine.

data['timestamp']  = pd.to_datetime(data['timestamp'])

data['Anomaly'] = 0

for start, end in anomaly_points:
    data.loc[((data['timestamp']>=start) & (data['timestamp']<=end)),'Anomaly'] = 1

# Distribution plot for temperature by year
year_2013_dist = hv.Distribution(data.loc[data['year'] == 2013, 'value'], label='2013')
year_2014_dist = hv.Distribution(data.loc[data['year'] == 2014, 'value'], label='2014')
temperature_by_year = (year_2013_dist * year_2014_dist).opts(
    title="Temperature by Year Distribution", legend_position='bottom'
)

# Distribution plot for temperature by month
month_12_dist = hv.Distribution(data.loc[data['month'] == 12, 'value'], label='12')
month_1_dist = hv.Distribution(data.loc[data['month'] == 1, 'value'], label='1')
month_2_dist = hv.Distribution(data.loc[data['month'] == 2, 'value'], label='2')
temperature_by_month = (month_12_dist * month_1_dist * month_2_dist).opts(
    title="Temperature by Month Distribution", legend_position='bottom'
)

# Combine the two Distribution plots
combined_plot = (temperature_by_year + temperature_by_month).opts(
    opts.Distribution(xlabel="Temperature", ylabel="Density", width=380, height=300,
                      tools=['hover'], show_grid=True)
)

microsoft aomaly detector¶
In [23]:
API_KEY = os.environ['ANOMALY_DETECTOR_API_KEY']
ENDPOINT = os.environ['ANOMALY_DETECTOR_ENDPOINT']
DATA_PATH = "./nab/realKnownCause/realKnownCause/machine_temperature_system_failure.csv"  # Example: c:\\test\\request-data.csv
CHUNK_SIZE = 5000  # Number of data points per request

client = AnomalyDetectorClient(ENDPOINT, AzureKeyCredential(API_KEY))

data_file = pd.read_csv(DATA_PATH)
timestamps = pd.to_datetime(data_file['timestamp'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
ax.plot(timestamps, data_file['value'], color='blue', label='Normal Data')

start_index = 0
total_points = len(data_file)
while start_index < total_points:
    end_index = min(start_index + CHUNK_SIZE, total_points)
    series = []
    for index, row in data_file.iloc[start_index:end_index].iterrows():
        series.append(TimeSeriesPoint(timestamp=row['timestamp'], value=row['value']))

    request = UnivariateDetectionOptions(series=series)
    change_point_response = client.detect_univariate_change_point(request)
    anomaly_response = client.detect_univariate_entire_series(request)

    for i, is_change_point in enumerate(change_point_response.is_change_point):
        if is_change_point:
            index = start_index + i
            ax.axvline(timestamps[index], color='orange', linestyle='--', linewidth=1, label='Change Point')

    for i, is_anomaly in enumerate(anomaly_response.is_anomaly):
        if is_anomaly:
            index = start_index + i
            ax.scatter(timestamps[index], data_file['value'][index], color='red', marker='o', label='Anomaly')

    start_index += CHUNK_SIZE

ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.AutoDateLocator())
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.xlabel('Timestamp')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.title('Anomaly Detection')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [24]:
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

# Assuming you have the true ground truth labels stored in the 'data' DataFrame column 'Anomaly'
ground_truth_labels = data['Anomaly'].astype(int)  # Convert to integer type (0 for normal, 1 for anomaly)

# Initialize an empty list to accumulate predicted labels
predicted_labels = []

for start_index in range(0, len(data_file), CHUNK_SIZE):
    end_index = min(start_index + CHUNK_SIZE, len(data_file))
    series = [TimeSeriesPoint(timestamp=row['timestamp'], value=row['value']) for index, row in data_file.iloc[start_index:end_index].iterrows()]

    request = UnivariateDetectionOptions(series=series)
    anomaly_response = client.detect_univariate_entire_series(request)

    # Accumulate the predicted labels
    predicted_labels.extend([1 if is_anomaly else 0 for is_anomaly in anomaly_response.is_anomaly])

# Calculate the F1 score
f1 = f1_score(ground_truth_labels, predicted_labels)
print("F1 Score:", f1)


Roc = roc_auc_score(ground_truth_labels, predicted_labels)
print("ROC Score:", Roc)

F1 Score: 0.2827480916030534
ROC Score: 0.5887566008056047
